abstract: A French court found Bob Denard, left, France's best-known mercenary, guilty of mounting a coup in the Comoro Islands off southeast Africa in 1995 and gave him a five-year suspended sentence. Twenty-six accomplices drew lesser sentences. The coup was ended after two weeks when the mercenaries surrendered to the French Army and freed the president they had taken hostage. Mr. Denard, 77, who was born Gilbert Bourgeaud before he gave himself the rank of colonel and a new name, was excused from testifying because doctors said he had Alzheimer's disease. He is said to be the model for the lead character in Frederick Forsyth's 1974 novel

abstract: A Yemeni judge has ordered the detention of Jaber Elbaneh, a Yemeni- American accused in terrorist plots who had been living free despite a $5 million American bounty on his head. American prosecutors won the indictment of Mr. Elbaneh in 2003, accusing him of being part of a group of young men from Lackawanna, N.Y., who had traveled to Afghanistan to train at a camp of Al Qaeda. Mr. Elbaneh, 41, was convicted last fall of conspiring to blow up oil installations in Yemen. He had been allowed to remain free during his appeal, which angered American authorities. While a judge ordered his detention on Sunday, it was not clear on Monday whether he had in fact been detained.
